Cook,<br><br>
If you believe the present Vietnam regime tells the truth, this is cause for reflection. However, I fear they continue to be masters of manipulation of the press and present only what they want to be seen. <br><br>
I wonder of David Lamb wants to cover the ongoing persecution of the Buddhists in that country. It is my understanding that the Vietnamese government is trying to create a state run Buddhist religion because they broke their deal with the Buddhists who helped them with the war. The Buddhists are not happy or conforming, so out they go! <br>
Remember Tay Ninh and Nui Ba Den? It is not circumstance that VC HQ was right over the border from there. The Buddhists were still fighting a religious war with a Cathoilic religion majority who was in power throughout much of Vietnam's colonial and puppet government years. The Buddhist Monks burning themselves alive in the streets of Saigon is still a compelling image. (These people were *true* protestors.)<br><br>
It really sounds good, but I do not think it is the Veteran's paradise they portray.<br><br>
Culturally, however, the Vietnamese people themselves are more extended family oriented, and I can see where a disabled Vet would have a better chance at humane and comforting treatment. We still like to lock up people who are &quot;different or defective&quot; and forget them.<br><br>
I guess I am just a plain old cynic, and an angry one, at that!.<br><br>
It burns me up, though, when I reminisce about us and the &quot;treatment&quot; we continue to receive. It is a shame that our supporters were never as vocal as the trash who spat upon us. We were sent *by* and *for* the United States. To have the country continue to ignore us and treat *us* poorly because the Vietnam War was a shamefull &quot;mistake&quot; is sick. We did not create the war, we only fought in it as patriotic Warriors. <br><br>
I agree with you, though, that:<br><br>
&quot;We are here because we did a soldier's duty.&quot;<br><br>
I know I am.<br><br>
